<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-5-5" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>A Convolution Theorem and its Applications</title>
    <introduction>
        <p> A crucial step in solving a linear initial value problem using Laplace transforms is
            determining the inverse Laplace transform of the solution’s Laplace transform. This step
            can become challenging when the expression, whose inverse Laplace transform is desired,
            is complicated. In this section, we discuss a procedure with which we can determine the
            inverse Laplace transform of an expression that is a product of known Laplace
            transforms. For example, we recall that <me>\mathcal
            {L}^{-1}\left\{\ds\frac{1}{s^2}\right\}
                = t \quad \text{ and }\quad \mathcal {L}^{-1}\left\{\ds\frac{2}{s^3}\right\} = t^2.</me>
            However, if we were to compute <me>\mathcal {L}^{-1}\left\{\ds\left(\frac{1}{s^2}\right)
            \left(\frac{2}{s^3}\right)\right\},</me> a direct way is to see this problem as <me>\mathcal
            {L}^{-1}\left\{\frac{2}{s^5}\right\}
                = \frac{2}{4!}\; t^4 = \frac{t^4}{12}.</me> This leads to a natural question: in
            what way can we combine <m>t</m> and <m>t^2</m> to produce <m>t^4/12</m>? The operation
            for combining inverse Laplace transforms—specifically, to determine the inverse of a
            product—is known as <em>
                convolution</em>, which is formalized in the following definition. </p>

        <definition xml:id="def-convolution">
            <statement>
                <p> Let <m>f</m> and <m>g</m> be functions on <m>[0, \infty).</m> The <term>
                        <em>convolution</em>
                    </term> of <m>f</m> and <m>g</m>,
                    denoted by <m>f\ast
                        g</m>, is the function defined by <me>(f\ast g)(t) = \int_0^t f(u) g(t-u)\,
                    du</me> whenever the integral exists for a given <m>t</m> in <m>[0, \infty).</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </definition>

        <p> For computational purposes, <m>(f * g)(t)</m> may also be written as <m>f(t) * g(t)</m>.
            It can be proved that <m>f\ast g = g\ast f;</m> see, for example, <xref
                ref="exercise-5-5-2-ii" /> in <xref
                ref="exercises-convolution-theorem" />. The convolution <m>1\ast
                f</m> is particularly useful, and it is given by <me>
                (1\ast f)(t) = \int_0^t f(u) \, du.
            </me> See, also, <xref
                ref="exercise-5-5-2-v" /> in <xref ref="exercises-convolution-theorem" />. </p>
        <example>
            <p> Let us return to the example discussed before <xref ref="def-convolution" /> and
                calculate the convolution of <m>f(t) =t</m> and <m>g(t) =t^2</m>. We have <me>\begin{split}
                (f\ast g)(t)&amp; = \int_0^t u (t-u)^2\, du\\
                    &amp;= \int_0^t (t^2u-2tu^2 +u^3)\, du\\
                    &amp;= \left[t^2\frac{u^2}{2}-2t\frac{u^3}{3}+\frac{u^4}{4}\right]_0^t\\
                &amp;=\frac{t^4}{2}-\frac{2t^4}{3}+\frac{t^4}{4}\\
                    &amp;=\frac{t^4}{12},
                    \end{split}</me> as expected. </p>
        </example>


    </introduction>
    <subsection xml:id="theorem-convolution">
        <title>Convolution Theorem</title>
        <p>
            We now state and prove the most important theorem of this section.
        </p>
        <theorem xml:id="thm-convolution">
            <statement>
                <p> Let <m>f</m> and <m>g</m> be piecewise continuous functions on <m>[0,\infty)</m>
                    and of the exponential order <m>\alpha</m> as <m>t\to\infty</m>. Then <me>\mathcal {L}\{(f\ast
                    g)(t)\}= F(s) \,G(s);</me> or equivalently, <me>\mathcal {L}^{-1}\left\{ F(s)
                    G(s)\right\} =\mathcal {L}^{-1}\{F(s)\}\ast \mathcal {L}^{-1}\{G(s)\} = (f\ast
                    g)(t)</me> for <m>
                        s&gt;\alpha.</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </theorem>
        <p>
            To see how this theorem holds, we need to use a method for changing the order of an
            iterated integral. We include a proof of the Convolution Theorem below for the sake of
            completeness; however, not to be distracted from the proof, the reader may choose to
            skip it for now and proceed directly to apply the theorem.
        </p>
        <proof>
            <title>Proof of <xref ref="thm-convolution" /></title>
            <p> We recall that <me>F(s) = \int_0^\infty e^{-s\eta} f(\eta) \, d\eta\quad \text{ and
                }\quad
                    G(s) = \int_0^\infty e^{-su} g(u) \, du.</me> Then <me>
                    \begin{split}
                    F(s) G(s) &amp; = \int_0^\infty e^{-s\eta} f(\eta) \, d\eta\; \int_0^\infty
                e^{-su} g(u) \, du\\
                    &amp;=\int_0^\infty g(u) \left( \int_0^\infty e^{-s(\eta+u)} f(\eta) \, d\eta
                \right) \, du\\
                    &amp; = \int_0^\infty g(u) \left( \int_u^\infty e^{-st} f(t - u) \, d\xi \right)
                \, du,
                    \end{split}</me> where <m>t=\eta+u.</m> By changing the order of integration, we
                obtain <me>\begin{split}
                    F(s) G(s)&amp;=\int_0^\infty e^{-s t} \left( \int_0^t g(u) f(t - u) \, du
                    \right) \, dt \\
                    &amp;=\int_0^\infty e^{-st} (g\ast f)(t)\, dt\\
                    &amp; = \mathcal {L}\{(f\ast g)(t)\}.
                    \end{split}</me>
            </p>
        </proof>
        <p> Some fundamental properties of the convolution operation are discussed in <xref
                ref="exercises-convolution-theorem" />; see the problem <xref
                ref="exercise-5-5-2-ii" />. </p>

    </subsection>
    <subsection xml:id="subsec-application-convolution">
        <title>Application of the Convolution Theorem to Initial Value Problems</title>
        <p> The following theorem concerns an interesting application of <xref
                ref="thm-convolution" /> to linear initial value problems that involve the Dirac
            delta functions. </p>
        <theorem xml:id="thm-application-convolution">
            <statement>
                <p> Let <m>y_\delta(t)</m> denote the solution of the initial value problem <men
                        xml:id="IVP-delta1">
                        ay''+by'+cy = \delta(t), \quad y(0) = 0, y'(0) = 0.
                    </men>
                    The the solution <m>y(t)</m> of the initial value problem <men
                        xml:id="IVP-delta2">
                        ay''+by'+cy = g(t), \quad y(0) = 0, y'(0) = 0
                    </men>
                    where <m>a, b, c</m> are constants with <m>a\ne 0,</m> and <m>g</m> is a
                    piecewise continuous function that is of exponential order as <m>
                        t\to\infty,</m> is given by <me>y(t) = (y_\delta \ast g)(t).</me>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </theorem>

        <p> We first remark that <m>y'</m> and <m>y''</m> in <xref ref="IVP-delta1" /> are to be
            interpreted differently (as <em>distributional derivatives</em>) because of the presence
            of <m>\delta(t)</m> on the right side of the equation. The fact beyond the scope of this
            book is that the Laplace transforms of distributional derivatives coincide with the
            Laplace transforms of the classical derivatives. </p>


        <proof>
            <title>Proof of <xref ref="thm-application-convolution" /></title>
            <p> We first find the solution of the initial value problem <xref
                    ref="IVP-delta1" />. Applying the Laplace transform <m>\mathcal{L}</m> to the initial
                value problem <xref ref="IVP-delta1" /> and using <m>y(0)= y'(0)=0</m> yields <me>(as^2+bs
                +c)Y_\delta(s)= 1,</me>that is, <me>Y_\delta(s)= \frac{1}{as^2+bs +c}.</me> Then, by
                taking the inverse Laplace transform, we have <me>y_\delta(t)
                    = \mathcal{L}^{-1}\left\{\frac{1}{as^2 + bs + c}\right\}.</me> Next, we take the
                Laplace transform of both sides of the equation in <xref ref="IVP-delta2" /> to get <me>Y(s)
                = \frac{G(s)}{as^2 + bs + c} = G(s) Y_\delta(s).</me> Finally, by applying the
                convolution theorem (<xref ref="thm-convolution" />), we conclude that <me>y(t) =
                (y_\delta \ast g)(t)</me> solves the initial value problem <xref ref="IVP-delta2" />
                . </p>
        </proof>
        <example>
            <p> Consider the initial value problem <m>y''+ y= e^t,\; y(0) = y'(0)= 0.</m> To solve
                this problem, we first find the solution of the initial value problem <m>y''+ y=
                \delta(t),\; y(0) = y'(0)= 0.</m> Applying the Laplace transform to this problem
                yields <me>(s^2 + 1) Y_\delta(s) = 1,</me> that is, <me>Y_\delta(s) = \frac{1}{s^2 +
                1}.</me> Then, by taking the inverse Laplace transform, we have <me>y_\delta(t) =
                \sin t.</me> Finally, by applying <xref ref="thm-application-convolution" /> with <m>
                g(t) = e^t</m>, we conclude that <me>y(t) = y_\delta(t) \ast e^t = \sin t \ast e^t =
                -\frac{1}{2}\left(-e^t+\sin t+\cos t\right)</me> on <m>(-\infty, \infty).</m>
            </p>
        </example>
    </subsection>


    <exercises xml:id="exercises-convolution-theorem">
        <exercise xml:id="exercise-5-5-1">
            <p> For the functions <m>f</m> and <m>g</m> on <m>[0, \infty)</m> given below, compute <m>f\ast
                g</m>, <m>\mathcal{L}\{(f\ast g)(t) \}</m> and verify that <m>\mathcal{L}\{(f\ast g)(t) \}
                =\mathcal{L}\{f(t)\}\, \mathcal{L}\{g(t)\}.</m> In the following, <m>k</m> and <m>\omega</m> are any
                real numbers. </p>
            <ol marker="i.">
                <li xml:id="exercise-5-5-1-i">
                    <p>
                        <m>f(t) = g(t) = 1</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="exercise-5-5-1-ii">
                    <p>
                        <m>f(t) = g(t) = e^{kt}</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="exercise-5-5-1-iii">
                    <p>
                        <m>f(t) = \sin t,\; g(t) = e^{kt}</m>
                    </p>

                </li>
                <li xml:id="exercise-5-5-1-iv">
                    <p>
                        <m>f(t)= g(t) = \sin (\omega t)</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="exercise-5-5-1-v">
                    <p>
                        <m>f(t)= \sin(\omega t),\; g(t) = \cos(\omega t)</m>

                    </p>
                </li>

            </ol>
        </exercise>
        <exercise xml:id="exercise-5-5-2">
            <p> Let <m>f, g, h</m> be functions defined on the interval <m>[0, \infty)</m>, and
                assume that all the convolutions below are well-defined. Use the definition of the
                convolution to prove the following properties. </p>
            <ol marker="i.">
                <li xml:id="exercise-5-5-2-i">
                    <p>
                        <m>f\ast g = g\ast f.</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="exercise-5-5-2-ii">
                    <p>
                        <m>f\ast (g\ast h) = (f\ast g)\ast h</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="exercise-5-5-2-iii">
                    <p>
                        <m>f\ast (g + h) = f\ast g + f\ast h</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="exercise-5-5-2-iv">
                    <p>
                        <m>f\ast (k g) = k (f\ast g)</m> for any constant <m>k</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="exercise-5-5-2-v">
                    <p>
                        <m>(1\ast f)(t) = \int_0^t f(u) \, du.</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="exercise-5-5-3">
            <p> Use the convolution theorem (<xref ref="thm-convolution" />) to find the Laplace
                transform of each of the following functions. </p>
            <ol marker="i." cols="2">
                <li xml:id="exercise-5-5-3-i">
                    <p>
                        <m>1\ast t\ast t^2</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="exercise-5-5-3-iii">
                    <p>
                        <m>1\ast t^2\ast \sin t</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="exercise-5-5-3-iv">
                    <p>
                        <m>1\ast \cos t\ast \sin t</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="exercise-5-5-3-v">
                    <p>
                        <m>1\ast \sin t\ast \mathcal{U} (t-2)</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="exercise-5-5-3-vi">
                    <p>
                        <m>1\ast \mathcal{U} (t-2)\ast \mathcal{U} (t-5)</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="exercise-5-5-3-vii">

                    <p>
                        <m>\ds\int_0^t e^u\, du</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="exercise-5-5-3-viii">
                    <p>
                        <m>\ds\int_0^t \sin u\, du</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="exercise-5-5-3-ix">
                    <p>
                        <m>\ds\int_0^t u\sin u\, du</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="exercise-5-5-3-x">
                    <p>
                        <m>\ds\int_0^t \sin u\,\cos(t-u)\, du</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="exercise-5-5-3-xi">
                    <p>
                        <m>\ds t\int_0^t \sin u\,\cos(t-u)\, du</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="exercise-5-5-4">
            <p> Use the convolution theorem (<xref ref="thm-convolution" />) to find each of the
                following inverse Laplace transforms. </p>
            <ol marker="i." cols="2">
                <li xml:id="exercise-5-5-4-i">
                    <p>
                        <m>\ds\mathcal{L}^{-1}\left\{\frac{1}{(s+1)(s-1)}\right\}</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="exercise-5-5-4-ii">
                    <p>
                        <m>\ds\mathcal{L}^{-1}\left\{\frac{1}{s^3(s-1)}\right\}</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="exercise-5-5-4-iii">
                    <p>
                        <m>\ds\mathcal{L}^{-1}\left\{\frac{2}{(s^2+4)^2}\right\}</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="exercise-5-5-4-iv">
                    <p>
                        <m>\ds\mathcal{L}^{-1}\left\{\frac{s^2}{(s^2+4)^2}\right\}</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="exercise-5-5-4-v">
                    <p>
                        <m>\ds\mathcal{L}^{-1}\left\{\frac{s^2}{(s^2-4)^2}\right\}</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="exercise-5-5-4-vi">
                    <p>
                        <m>\ds\mathcal{L}^{-1}\left\{\frac{1}{s^2(s^2+4)^2}\right\}</m>
                    </p>
                </li>

            </ol>
        </exercise>
        <exercise xml:id="exercise-5-5-5">
            <p>
                Solve the following integral or integro-differential equations using the Laplace
                transform.
            </p>
            <ol marker="i.">
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <m>\ds y(t)+\int_0^t y(u)\, du = 1</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <m>\ds y(t) = te^t+ \int_0^t u\,y(t-u)\, du</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <m>\ds y'(t) = 1-\cos t - \int_0^t y(u)\, du, \quad y(0) =0</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <m>\ds y'(t) +4 y(t) + 4 \int_0^t y(u)\, du=1, \quad y(0) =0</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="exercise-5-5-6">
            <p> Use <xref ref="thm-application-convolution" /> to solve the following initial value
                problems. </p>
            <ol marker="i.">
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <m>y'-3y= \sin t, \quad y(0)= 0</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <m>y''+y= \sin t, \quad y(0)= 0, \; y'(0)=0</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <m>y''+4y'+3y= e^t, \quad y(0)= 0, \; y'(0)=0</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <m>y''+4y'+13y= \cos t, \quad y(0)= 0, \; y'(0)=0</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="exercise-5-5-7">
            <p> Let <m>f</m> be a continuous function defined on the interval <m>[0, \infty)</m>,
                and assume that all the convolutions below are well-defined. Show the following
                properties of the convolution operation. </p>
            <ol marker="i.">
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <m>f\ast \delta = f.</m> (This means that <m>\delta</m> is an identity
                        element for the convolution operation.) </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <m>f(t)\ast \delta (t-a) = \mathcal{U}(t-a) f(t-a),</m> where <m>a\ge 0</m>
                        and is a fixed real number. </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="exercise-5-5-8">
            <p> Let <m>f, g</m> be functions with continuous derivatives on the interval <m>[0,
                \infty)</m> and of exponential order as <m>t\to\infty</m>. Assume further that all
                the convolutions below are well-defined. Use the convolution theorem (<xref
                    ref="thm-convolution" />) to prove the following properties. </p>
            <ol marker="i.">
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <m>1\ast f'(t) = f(t) - f(0).</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <m>(f\ast g)'(t) = g(0) f(t) + (g'\ast f)(t) = f(0) g(t) + (g\ast f')(t).</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
            <remarks>
                <p> The above properties are also valid for any differentiable functions <m>f</m>
                    and <m>g</m>, not necessarily of exponential order as <m>t\to\infty</m>, in
                    light of the Leibniz rule<fn>
                        <men xml:id="Leibniz-rule">
                            \begin{split}
                            \frac{d}{dt}\int_{a(t)}^{b(t)} f(u, t) \, du \amp =
                            f(b(t), t) \frac{db(t)}{dt} - f(a(t), t)\frac{da(t)}{dt}\\
                            \amp +\int_{a(t)}^{b(t)} \frac{\partial f}{\partial t} (u, t)\, du
                    \end{split}
                        </men>
                    </fn>
                    for differentiating an integral (see <xref
                        ref="thm-Leibnitz-Rule-Improper-Integrals" />). </p>
            </remarks>
        </exercise>
        <exercise xml:id="exercise-5-5-9">
            <p> By using the Leibniz rule <xref ref="Leibniz-rule" />, convert each of the following
                integral or integro-differential equations into an equivalent initial value problem
                and then solve it by using your favorite method. Compare your answers to those
                obtained in <xref ref="exercise-5-5-5" />. </p>
            <ol marker="i.">
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <m>\ds y(t)+\int_0^t y(u)\, du = 1</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <m>\ds y(t) = te^t+ \int_0^t u\,y(t-u)\, du</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <m>\ds y'(t) = 1-\cos t - \int_0^t y(u)\, du, \quad y(0) =0</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <m>\ds y'(t) +4 y(t) + 4 \int_0^t y(u)\, du=1, \quad y(0) =0</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="exercise-5-5-10">
            <p>
                Solve the following initial value problems using the Laplace transform. Also,
                determine whether the solutions are continuous at the point(s) of concentration of
                the involved Dirac delta functions(s).
            </p>
            <ol marker="i.">
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <m>y'-3y= \delta(t-1), \quad y(0)= 0</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <m>y'+4y= \delta(t-2), \quad y(0)= 1</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <m>y''+4y= \delta(t-2\pi), \quad y(0)= 0, \; y'(0)=0</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <m>y''+4y'+3y= \delta(t-2\pi), \quad y(0)= 0, \; y'(0)=0</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <m>y''+4y'+13y= \delta(t-2\pi), \quad y(0)= 0, \; y'(0)=0</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <m>y''+4y'+3y= \delta(t-2\pi) +\delta(t-3\pi), \quad y(0)= 0, \; y'(0)=0</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <m>y''+4y'+13y= \delta(t-2\pi) +\delta(t-3\pi), \quad y(0)= 0, \; y'(0)=0</m>
                    </p>
                </li>

            </ol>
        </exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="exercise-5-5-11">
        <p> A 32 lb mass stretches a vertically hanging spring 4 feet to equilibrium. The mass
            is then pulled down 1 foot and released from rest. Assume no damping or external
            forces. Let <m>y(t)</m> denote the displacement of the mass from equilibrium at time <m>
            t,</m> measured positive in the downward direction. (Use <m>g= 32
            \;\text{ft}/\text{s}^2</m>.) </p>
        <ol marker ="i.">
            <li xml:id="exercise-5-5-11-i">
                <p> Set up an initial value problem for <m>y(t).</m>
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="exercise-5-5-11-ii">
                <p>
                    Determine a Dirac delta function that models the impulsive force on the mass
                    exerted by striking it with a hammer to stop it at the first time it passes
                    through equilibrium, keeping it at the equilibrium position thereafter.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="exercise-5-5-11-iii">
                <p>
                    Repeat <xref ref="exercise-5-5-11-ii" /> to stop the mass at the second time it passes through equilibrium.
                </p>
            </li>
        </ol>

    </exercise>
    </exercises>
</section>